segments.text: Oh, yeah.
Those things were applied to a lot of the professors.
What was your major and why?
Ag economics.
I started doing this lecture planning here.
And I found out pretty quick that my background in math wasn't strong enough to do that.
So, in fact, the first semester I hadn't made a B in B.E.O.
and I had my ten hours until grade points to stay in.
So I changed over to ag economics.
I had a rural farm background anyway.
And I enjoyed it.
What did you think you were preparing to do?
I had no earthly idea.
Why did you go to college in the first place?
Well, because when I was in high school, getting up at 4.30 in the morning and going and milking them darn cows before I went to school wasn't the thing I wanted to do all my life.
Your parents encouraged you?
Yes.
Do you remember about what it cost a year to go?
I have, still have, some receipts.
And it seemed like a room and board was about thirty something dollars.
I don't know where that was, a month or a semester.
I'm not sure.
But I've still got the receipts back in my old... Did you have a job on campus?
I worked part-time.
Where?
I worked some in the mess hall.
And then I got a job with one of the office supply guys there in town.
Selling office supplies out over the country, you know, making food, fixing the dining box and places like that, and snow.
That wasn't much of a sale.
That didn't last too long.
In Ag-ECO, were there, remember any special teachers?
Dan Russell, do you have him?
Dr. Dan, the grade point man?
I believe I did.
I believe I did.
And I'm sure, I've said it long enough, I can probably recall some of them.
Let's see, let's digress on where did all the veterans and their wives live?
Well, a lot of the veterans lived in a new area across the North Gate, and there were apartments east of there that a lot of the veterans lived with wives.
And did they change the atmosphere in the classroom?
I don't think so.
My freshman year, we had gotten very, very few veterans.
My sophomore and junior year, they began to get quite few.
But I'm assuming that they were serious, determined.
Well, some were, and some were joined right in with us with a couple of them.
Let's see.
Activities.
What role did the YMCA building play?
What happened over there?
I really never went there.
I don't know that I... Guyon Hall?
Guyon Hall was our theater.
Our movie house.
All of their...
PE and stuff like that or intramurals was, I guess it was all right there on the east campus.
Didn't have anything gross on the street at that time for intramurals.
The old real field review was probably the best.
One thing that in final review, but I don't know when they quit this practice,
When we were freshmen, we had a fish trap on our farm.
And that was the time you got to pull your fish trap off, or if you were a search bug, for instance, you got to take right off your hip.
All those kind of things.
I don't know whether to do that now or not, but I went back and some of my old memorabilia, I had some of those things.
And I give a display to the Corps Center.
It was there for a long time.
I don't know if it's still there or not.
And where did final review take place?
It was the old real field.
Do you remember your final review?
No, my final review, let me tell you, my final review, I didn't even get a stay for graduation.
My father had had a heart attack, and I had to leave, and I graduated in December, or January when it was, instead of fall term.
And I had to leave about eight or ten days before my graduation to go back out and take over the business.
So you didn't get to have that?
No, they just sent me another problem.
I didn't even get to graduate.
Before your own commencement, did you go to other graduation ceremonies?
I don't remember any.
Were there any famous visitors to the campus that you remember during your student days?
Yeah, but I couldn't recall anything.
But we had to know for our junior prom and senior ring dance and things like that.
We had people like Sandy Kate, Darce Day, Bob Hope came to campus one time.
That's when the Aggieland Inn was on campus.
I know I was working that day and I had to assist Doris Day with her bags after her run.
I thought, my gosh, she's the most freckle-faced woman I ever saw in my life.
Of course, you don't see that on the stage.
Any important politicians, governors, presidents, generals?
We had a lot of military people.
And I'm sure we had some governors come, but in that day and time it really impressed me that much.
Uh, religious activities during your student days?
Yeah, I belonged to the church there at Northgate, the Baptist church.
And they had several social activities for those Aggies.
Did you Aggies go to Sunday service?
Yeah, most of us.
Was there religious emphasis week then?
I don't know.
I don't remember.
That was going on when I got there.
It would be a week in the spring and we'd have a speaker in Guyon Hall and so forth.
I'm sure it probably was, but I just don't remember.
All right, let's talk about the diversity.
Basically, in terms of religious preference, the student body was what?
I'd say it was generally majority Protestant.
Did you have any Catholic friends, acquaintances?
Yes.
Were there any Jewish students?
Not a whole lot.
There might have been a few, but not a lot.
Any international students or any students who came from some other... Not like it is now.
You know, we might have had...
We might have had, you know, a sprinkling of students from Mexico.
Were they treated differently?
No.
Not that I can remember.
And where did they live?
Were they part of the...
They were part of the Corps and everything else.
Do you remember anybody who seemed unusually rich?
No, and that's one thing I liked about any of them.
If they were... Enlarge on that point.
Well, if somebody came to A&M and had a million dollars in their back pocket, they didn't have a penny in their pocket.
They were still all on the same level.
Everybody respected everybody, and it wasn't the amount of money you had to make your chance in life at A&M.
It was a lot of other things.
And, you know, I really liked that.
Did it matter where you came from geographically?
No, it sure didn't.
As you look back on it, was the leadership composed of any certain segment of the student body?
Well, you know, I mean, like your class officers were basically pretty popular.
No, but I mean, to be one of those, did you have to be from a certain place or a certain major?
No.
I don't know.
And how many do you think of your associates were from college educated parents?
I'd say that there was, it'd be a rough guess, but I would be thinking it'd be less than good to be honest.
My parents weren't.
I'll bet that's a safe guess.
Let's see, what did these veterans' wives do?
They couldn't go to class, except in the summer, so what did they do?
A lot of them worked as secretaries and things like that.
And a lot of them were just housewives, I guess.
Did these veterans cause any changes in campus traditions?
None that I know of.
They were a little reluctant, of course, to walk in the gutter and say, I didn't have a freshman, but...
You know, other than a few things like that, I think they respect the tradition.
Let's see, we talked about hitchhiking.
Did you ever much ride the train or the bus?
Yes.
Describe those experiences.
I rode the train, catch the train in Little Hill, Texas, which is 20 miles from Springwood, and ride to Covey Station on the train.
What?
What route was that?
Gosh, I don't know.
Did you change?
I think we changed.
It was Santa Fe, the left Littlefield.
And I don't know.
What is that line, Joseph?
I'm not sure.
I think it used to be Southern Pacific.
Yeah, I don't think it was Santa Fe.
So we had to change somewhere.
But, yeah, we've done that many times.
Bus.
Occasionally we'd take the bus.
Where did you catch it?
You can catch the bus in Littleville too.
No, but then in College Station if you want.
Oh, it seemed to me like there was a place up in Northgate where you caught the bus.
Let's see.
On El Campus, where did an Aggie get a date?
Well, that's kind of a funny thing, but when we had our court trips to Fort Worth and to Dallas,
we'd try to contact some Tessies, students from TSC Kentucky, which then was a normal female school.
And on numerous occasions, we'd write this student a box with a box number and write a letter, and you'd be surprised how many blind dates you could pick up that way.
But other than that, there wasn't a lot of women around Bryan College Stationery for dating, and we really didn't.
Did you or any of your buddies ever have any interesting test seat blind date experiences you can share?
We've had some.
I've had some.
I can't remember.
One of my good buddies, Bill Burrow, finally married one that he blind dated.
Describe a court trip weekend.
Well, it alternated Fort Worth one year to Dallas the next year, and the whole Corps would go up and march in the town before the game that morning, or before that afternoon.
How'd you get there?
Well, most of us had shacks.
And you spent the night?
And tonight, you know, we'd bundle up a bunch of us in a hotel room and stuff like that.
Anything ever happen on Saturday night?
Well, we had our midnight yell practices there, wherever we were, we had them.
And, oh, there's a few fisticuffs around town, things like that, but not anything extraordinary.
In general, how were the dates treated?
I don't know what you mean by that, but I think an Aggie is a gentleman, and the women they dated, they were treated very properly.
That's the direction I was assuming.
And what was expected that the Aggie would do for his date that weekend?
Well, he was just kind of, if it was a date that they had out of town to come in,
They would be as an escort to do different affairs and things and take them to all the festivities.
Would there be a dance that night?
Sometimes there wasn't, sometimes there wasn't.
And then y'all would come home about Sunday morning?
Yeah, start trickling in on Sunday morning.
And then also went to Houston and Austin.
Of the court trip.
I don't remember coming to Austin.
Oh, y'all didn't do it?
I don't think we did.
Oh, okay.
No, that's right.
And didn't do court trips to Waco.
No.
When you came home, were you kind of worn out after a court trip weekend?
Oh, young Buck, him days don't get worn out.
I wish I had the energy now.
I did then.
Let's see.
Special social events at College Station.
What were they?
Well, some of the dances I mentioned to you a moment ago.
And it was very special when you'd have a date come into town for a football weekend.
Because there was always something going on other than football.
I don't guess there's near as many special occasions as there are now on campus.
The same way the student programs.
We had very few clubs and student programs we participated in those days.
Now there's over seven of them, which I think is wonderful for a degree.
All right, you're now a senior.
What were the big social events of being a senior?
I guess you look forward to the senior ring dance, but not much of anything.
Boot bags?
Well, that's basically the same thing.
Oh, okay, okay.
Oh, yeah, yeah, that's right.
And that would have been held where?
We used to have it in Subesa.
And how was a young lady treated?
How did she dress and so forth?
That was kind of an obligation for a young lady to be farmer.
Let's see, did you ever have, did you have a car while you were a student?
I did my last, I think last semester or two, I bought an old record car.
And that day you could buy an old car for $50.
Oh, I see what you meant by record.
Yeah.
It's an old model.
I think I bought an old 32 model Chevrolet.
And so you finish in what year?
In January of 1950.
Okay, so you... Now, just before I finished that last semester, my father did buy me a car.
As a kind of a graduation present.
Let's see...
You're on the main campus now.
Where did you go off campus for a good time?
Well, I remember one evening when the battalion came out, it had an article in it about the girls in Temple, Texas that formed the Nagyette Club.
And the whole purpose was it was when Nagy's came into town, they'd get on blind dates.
So me and my roommate that afternoon, when that battalion came out, we went to Temple.
Tried out the situation, and it worked.
Well, the following two or three weekends, one of my roommates and I started Temple.
He was a big tall guy from Olsen, Texas.
And we had called the Aggie head president to get us dates.
And they did.
And we talked to them on the phone before we got there.
And Buddy being much taller than I was, one of these girls was quite a bit taller than the other.
And so I had a date with a taller girl.
He had a date with a shorter one.
So we switched and told them why.
It didn't make any difference to them.
But ironically, the girl I wound up with, the shorter one,
I finally married.
So that's how you met through?
That's how I met my wife.
Aggie Et Club.
Uh-huh, in Temple, Texas.
Now these Aggie Et dates were in high school or college age?
They were seniors in high school and junior college there and business college there in Temple.
Were there Aggie Et Clubs anywhere else?
I don't know that.
I've never, see you just added a new breadth, I've not heard of that before.
Alright, so you meet her that way, and you're what year in school?
This is my senior year.
Okay, and so you began to go to Temple more often then.
Okay, when she came to College Station, where would y'all go?
I don't know that she ever came to College Station.
Alright, did an Aggie go to the movie much?
And if so, where?
Well, like I said, we went to Cannon Hall a lot.
There wasn't much other.
I think there was one movie, North Campus, I mean Northgate.
But we didn't go to them.
Can you describe Northgate, what was out there?
Well, the Dixie Chicken wasn't out there then.
It was just, you know, a...
Lupo had his bookstore on the corner and then he had several little businesses if you went on down to where the theater was.
And it seemed to me like across the street east of Lupo's there was a couple of little businesses and a gas station and that was about it then.
Did you, were you students aware of Mr. Lupo?
Oh yes, I knew him well.
Please describe Mr. LePore.
Well, he was a great actor.
He was kind of like a Pinky Downs almost.
And was a great booster of A&M.
He helped many of the students.
How?
You know, some students come to A&M that didn't have a diamond scratcher.
And if they needed help with books and things, he'd make provisions where they could get books and take care of them later.
Things like that.
He was just a
He just believed in A&M 200%.
Was he sincere?
Oh, absolutely.
He really was.
And were his business practices fair and honest?
As far as I know, I never heard anybody complain.
Describe Mr. Lupo.
Well, he was a guy about my size, maybe a little heavier weight, and he was always in a talented mood.
That's really about as much as I remember about it individually.
And did you and other students buy books and things from him?
Yes.
Pinky Downs, who was he?
Pinky Downs was a little waggy promoter from way back.
I've got what class Pinky was in, but
I mean, he never missed a football game.
He never missed a baseball or basketball game.
He was all T.L.
practices.
And everybody thought of Pete Downs as one of the greatest O'Lakes.
And what did he do on campus?
Well, he was basically just a PR person, I guess.
I mean, he was top, top in A&M everywhere, any chance he had.
because he was still there when I got there in 59.
And the first time I saw Lupo was at a football scrimmage game, and here came this guy in a little late, yelling, gig'em, gig'em, gig'em, and I wondered, who in the world is that guy?
You know, Pinky Downs reminds me of a whole lot of, oh gosh, I'm proud to thank the guys associated with the football team now that does all the, keeps all the,
materials together, suits and things.
Billy Pickard.
Oh.
Pinky Downs was a whole lot like Billy Pickard.
Or Billy Pickard was a lot like Pinky Downs.
Let's see.
No, there were no campus incidents, no fires, no bombings, no during your time, whatever?
Do you remember any unusual?
I don't remember anything other than that March on Gilchrist Town.
All right.
Gilchrist is president when you get there.
Is he president throughout your?
No, I don't remember.
I flatly don't remember.
And you didn't go across the stage at commencement, so you don't remember who?
No.
So you got your diploma through the mail?
They sent it to me through the mail.
And did y'all worry much about grade point ratios?
Well, the only thing you had to worry about then was you had to have a 10-10 stand.
10 grade points and 10 hours.
But I found out myself, those first few semesters were the hardest.
Because after that, in our day and time, we could take as many hours as we wanted to.
I put 23 hours on my semester.
And after my first two semesters, I made A's and B's and a few sprinkles C's.
and never studied half as much.
It was just getting acclimatized to a routine and procedure.
And in a typical weekday, how many of those hours were you on the campus?
All the time.
So you were totally immersed.
Yeah.
Let's see, do you remember any international events during that time that caused you to kind of stop and pause and think about what it might mean?
Well, the war was over, but I think that happened just before my draft board told me that I could go into college.
It didn't where I would be able to continue
or where I'd be drafted in that first semester.
And I went ahead and went, and then the war was over, it cleared over.
And the draft then, the Nikes don't think we're going to college, and things like that.
And of course, that was a very memorable occasion, when Harris-Hammond, Thomas Hockey, or whatever it is, was bombed with an atomic bomb.
And you graduate in December or January of 1950, so before the Korean War.
A lot of my, most of it.
The reason I didn't go to the Korean War was because my father was an architect and he happened to assume the farming business.
But a lot of my buddies, I guess the majority of them, did go to the Korean War.
Most popular student indulgences of the time.
What did y'all...
I don't know.
I like different things.
Did anybody drink any beer in those days?
When they get to Anfield.
Where?
There was a place that, a couple places at Eastgate, that's heard there.
There were places over going into Bryan, the old Triangle.
We used to serve beer.
There wasn't a whole lot, but there were several.
What were the most popular brands for an idea?
Gosh, I don't know.
I don't remember at all.
Beer was beer then.
And whiskey?
Whiskey was always obtained from across the river at the bridge.
What about smoking?
You know, it didn't seem to me like...
Smoking was as popular then as it had gotten after then.
And what brands did the folks smoke?
Well, Chesterfields and Campbells.
Lucky Strike Green had gone to war, so it was Lucky Strike White.
Cigars?
Very few cigars.
Snuff?
Chewing tobacco?
There were a few of the guys that chewed with tobacco.
We mentioned hard lickers.
Was there any house of ill repute?
Well, of course, there was the chicken ranch, which is not too far because there's no other ranch.
But right around there, I don't know it.
Did you ever hear of the chicken ranch in those days?
Yeah, I think most Aggies heard it.
I don't know.
Did you know of any Aggies that...
admitted they'd been there?
No.
Let's see.
Once you got that car, did anybody ever borrow it or try to borrow it?
No, but I sure had a lot of people ride, more drives.
Normally when you gave somebody a ride out of town, what was the routine about the expenses?
They'd share the gas.
And if you had any money and you were going to really splurge, what did an Aggie spend his money on?
I don't know in that position.
I really don't know.
There wasn't much money to be splurged at that time.
Okay.
Going to play a football game in College Station.
And this is, you're a junior, a senior now.
Describe that whole weekend.
What went on and who and where and so forth.
Describe the football weekend.
Well, it was a whole weekend.
I guess the football game was a climax.
But leading up to the Y'all's Mid-Nine Hill practices was...
were really inspired.
They wasn't near the Grouse.
Where were they held?
Where were the Yale practice held?
You know, it seemed to me like we used to have in the new area, but I'm not sure.
Or are we dead out there on that old drill field behind Duncan Hall?
I don't remember doing it in Goff Hill until later years.
OK, then that's Friday night.
And who went to midnight Yale practice?
We all did.
Dates?
Yeah, yeah.
Dates they went with you.
Then Saturday, what time did things begin?
Well, Saturday began just like a regular military day.
You know, you had your practice.
Then from after that time until game time, you kind of went on your own.
You know, you got ready to do the march-in, which you had to do earlier for the game against Jordan.
And, of course, it wasn't as long a march-in then because it wasn't... Well, I guess they were, too.
There were just many of them.
There weren't more in the Corps then.
There were more.
And during the game, where were y'all and what'd you do?
We stood up all game.
And we humped it for Yale practice, up for our Yales.
